item.title: Trump Administration Weighs Troop Cut in South Korea
item.description: The Pentagon has presented the White House with options to reduce the American military presence in South Korea as the two countries remain at odds over President Trump’s demand that Seoul greatly increase how much it pays for the U.S. troops stationed in the country, U.S. officials said.

item.title: U.K.'s Johnson Accelerates Plan for Easing Lockdown
item.description: Prime Minister Boris Johnson said he hoped the country could return toward normalcy by Christmas, as he presented a provisional plan to ease coronavirus lockdown restrictions.

item.title: China and India Locked in High-Altitude Arms Race Along Disputed Frontier
item.description: Battle lines are hardening along the remote Himalayan frontier that separates China and India, where the two Asian giants have been engaged in a competitive military construction spree, expanding bases and building airfields to accommodate bigger and more heavily armed forces.

item.title: U.S. Protests Stir Scrutiny of Police Treatment of Indigenous People
item.description: Activists in Australia, New Zealand and Canada draw parallels between the death of George Floyd and police treatment of indigenous communities.

item.title: Saudi Arabia Wants Its Fugitive Spymaster Back
item.description: Officials say billions in a Saudi counterterrorism fund under the control of spy chief Saad al Jabri have gone missing. Jabri’s supporters say the money was used to fight terrorists and the system was approved by the former crown prince. Western officials are worried an investigation could expose secrets.
